The construction of cladograms based on base and amino acid sequences
only became possible towards the end of the 20th century. Before that
the sequence data was not available and computer software had not
been developed to do the analysis. The construction of cladograms and
identication of clades is known as cladistics.
Cladistics has caused some revolutions in plant and animal
classication. It is now clear from cladograms that traditional
classication based on morphology does not always match the
evolutionary origins of groups of species. As a result some groups have
been reclassied. Some groups have been merged, others have been
divided and in some cases species have been transferred from one
group to another.
Reclassication of groups of organisms is time-consuming and
potentially disruptive for biologists, but it is certainly worthwhile. The
new classications based on cladistics are likely to be much closer to
a truly natural classication so their predictive value will be higher.
They have revealed some unnoticed similarities between groups and
also some signicant differences between species previously assumed
to be similar.
